ce:section.ce:para:
SEM and XRD are employed to investigate the potential mechanism by which PASP/N-CDs inhibits CaSO4 scaling. Fig. 9
                         displays the XRD patterns for the CaSO4 scale formed in the testing solution with and without PASP and PASP/N-CDs. The observed diffraction peaks at 2θ values of 11.49°, 20.61°, 23.26°, and 29.01° (*) correspond to the peaks of gypsum diffraction at (0 2 0), (−1 2 1), (0 4 0), and (−1 4 1), in that order. The presence of PASP leads to a decrease in the intensity of the (0 2 0) and (0 4 0) diffraction peaks. This alteration is also reflected in the SEM images of the CaSO4 scale (Fig. 10
                        ). From Fig. 10, the CaSO4 scale formed in the blank test solution exhibits a complete rod-like appearance, and the growth of the crystals is regular (Fig. 10a, a′). After the addition of PASP, the average particle size of the CaSO4 crystals increases, and jagged defects appear on the crystal surfaces. (Fig. 10b, b′). It demonstrates PASP's inhibitory action on the CaSO4 scale. It is attributed to the chelation capacity of PASP and its adherence to the surfaces of CaSO4 microcrystals [46,47]. However, with the addition of PASP/N-CDs, the peak intensity at 2θ = 11° and 2θ = 23° significantly decrease, indicating a marked inhibition of the (0 2 0) and (0 4 0) crystal planes of CaSO4. After the addition of PASP/N-CDs, the CaSO4 crystals appear shattered from Fig. 10 (c, c′), presenting a completely disordered appearance with an increase in irregular particles. These data indicate that the addition of PASP/N-CDs distorts the lattice of CaSO4. Moreover, supplementary Fig. S3 shows the XRD pattern of the CaSO4 scale with the addition of N-CDs. The pattern is similar to that of the CaSO4 scale formed in the blank solution, indicating that the impact of N-CDs on the crystal structure of CaSO4 is negligible. This contrasts with the findings of Wang et al. that the addition of CCQDs resulted in the disappearance of peaks around 2θ = 11° and 2θ = 20° [23]. This discrepancy may arise from differences in surface-functional groups. The carboxyl groups on the surface of CCQDs are abundant, facilitating easy adsorption onto crystal surfaces. Simultaneously, the rapid motion of quantum dots intensifies the damage to CaSO4 crystals, thereby leading to lattice distortion. When N-CDs is modified with PASP, thereby enriching its surface with carboxyl groups, that it acquires the capability to induce lattice distortion in CaSO4 crystals.
